The office of the governor in Busia will receive the largest percentage increase in revenue allocation if the current budget estimates for the 2022-23 financial year are approved by the county assembly. Revenue allocated by the Assembly to Governor Sospeter Ojaamong’s office, according to estimates rose by 14.2 per cent to Sh556.1 million up from the previous fiscal year’s Sh486.7 million. The figure stood at Sh486.7 in 2021-22 financial year after recording a Sh81 million increase from Sh405.2 million it had been allocated in the 2020-21 fiscal year. The county chief is exiting office and is eyeing the Teso South parliamentary seat currently held by Geoffrey Omuse. According to the 2022-23 budget estimates seen by the Star, the Sh556.1 million will cater for both recurrent and development expenditure. From the amount, Sh438.1 million will be channeled to shoulder the burden of recurrent expenditure which also entails paying salaries for employees in the governor’s office. While Sh118 million will cater for development. OTHER SECTORS Interestingly, agriculture, the backbone of the county received the heaviest slash in revenue. According to the estimates, the department will receive Sh662 million of the Sh8.07 billion budgeted for in the 2022-23 financial year. This is Sh154.8 million down from the Sh776.8 million it received in the 2021-22 fiscal year. The largest part of Busia’s population depends on agriculture and agriculturalists have warned the budget cut may have far reaching consequences in the county’s efforts of becoming food secure. Majority of the residents in Busia are small holders farmers and some are beneficiaries of the county’s financial development programmes aimed at improving productivity. Among other departments that saw a rise in their revenue allocations included the department of education and vocational training whose budget has risen by Sh36.8 million to Sh603.1. The department had been allocated Sh562.8 in the 2020-21 budget. It was closely followed by health and sanitation which received a Sh22.5 million increase in allocation. The department’s proposed budget for the 2022-23 financial year stands at Sh2.31 billion having risen from the previous year’s 2.29 billion and Sh2.03 billion in 2020-21. The department has consistently received the largest share of the budget since Ojaamong got into office. Sports, culture and social services department was the only other department that saw its revenue increased. Its allocation increased by Sh6.03 million to Sh171 million from the previous year’s Sh164.9 million. The department had received Sh122.8 million in 2020-21 financial year. REVENUE CUTS Among departments that saw their revenue reduced, lands, housing and rrban development came closer to the department of agriculture after its revenue allocation dropped by Sh135 million from Sh446 million to the current estimates that put the figure at Sh311 million. It received Sh138 million in 2020-21 fiscal year. Water, irrigation, environment and natural resources stood at third position with a Sh84.9 million budget slash. The department that is expected to boost agricultural productivity in the county because of its irrigation component received an allocation of Sh330.8 million down from 2021-22 financial year’s Sh415.7 million allocation. The department had been given Sh369 million during the 2020-21 financial year. Roads, infrastructure and energy that suffered a Sh42.8 million revenue cut. The department that is critical in ensuring easy movement and trade flow was allocated Sh853.6 million. This was a drop compared to Sh896.4 million it received in the previous budget. The department was allocated Sh941.6 million in 2020-21. Trade, investment, industry and cooperatives whose budget was slashed by Sh42.5 million to Sh134.5 million from Sh177.05 million in the previous year. Public administration stood at position six among departments whose budgets were slashed. The department that received Sh356.3 million in 2021-22 financial year was allocated Sh325.3, down by Sh30.9 million. It had received Sh275.3 million in 2020-21 financial year. The county assembly came at position seven with a Sh25.6 million budget cut. The assembly according to the budget estimates has been allocated Sh880.7 million in the 2022-23 fiscal year, down from Sh906.4 million it received the previous year. The Assembly had been allocated Sh804.9 million in 2020-21 budget year. The departments of finance and economic planning as well as County Public Service Board respectively closed at position eight and nine among departments whose budgets were cut. The finance department suffered a Sh4.8 million budget slash leaving it with Sh831.9 million, down from Sh836.8 it received in the 2021-22 financial year. The department had received Sh755.5 million in the 2020-21 budget year. The CPSB was slapped with a Sh1.7 million budget cut having been allocated Sh97.2 million according to the current budget approximations. The board had been allocated Sh99.03 million and Sh65.2 million in the 2021-22 and 2020-21 financial years respectively. On Friday, Deputy governor Moses Mulomi said revenue growth in the county was critical and that there was need for concerted efforts to ensure all revenue lose loopholes are sealed. Finance Chief executive Phaustine Barasa said underperformance in the collection of local revenue has continued to be a challenge in the implementation of county projects. She said low local revenue streams had been worsened by the emergence of Covid-19 whose effects the county is still facing. (Edited by Tabnacha O)